{{Nihongo|'''Akira Yaegashi'''|八重樫 東|Yaegashi Akira|extra=born February 25, 1983}} is a [[Japan]]ese professional boxer who is the former [[World Boxing Association|WBA]] [[minimumweight]] champion. He is an alumnus of the [[Takushoku University]] and has been managed by [[Hideyuki Ohashi]]'s Ohashi Boxing Gym in [[Yokohama]] which is the birthplace of [[boxing]] in the country.<ref name="moxmob" /> He is recognized by the [http://www.tbrb.org/all-rankings/#122| Transnational Boxing Rankings Board] as the World Flyweight Champion.

==Boxing career==
Yaegashi finished his amateur career with a record of 56–14 after winning the Inter-High School Championship and the [[National Sports Festival of Japan]]. His professional debut was at the [[Yokohama Cultural Gymnasium]] in March 2005.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ohashi-gym.com/?boxer=yaegashi&style=licenseA|title=選手紹介|year=2012|publisher= Ohashi Boxing Gym|language=Japanese|accessdate=June 21, 2012}}</ref> He won the vacant [[Oriental and Pacific Boxing Federation|OPBF]] minimumweight title there via a fifth round technical knockout in April 2006 and defended the title once before vacating it.<ref name="moxmob" />

In his first world title shot against the [[World Boxing Council|WBC]] minimumweight champion [[Eagle Kyowa]] at the [[Pacifico Yokohama]] in June 2007, Yaegashi lost for the first time by a wide points margin after suffering a broken [[Temporomandibular joint|TMJ]]<ref name="moxmob" /> in two places due to an accidental headbutt in the second round.<ref name="daily201110">{{Cite web|url=http://www.daily.co.jp/ring/2011/10/25/0004572116.shtml|title=八重樫TKOで岩手出身初の世界王者!|date=October 25, 2011|publisher=''[[Kobe Shimbun|Daily Sports]]''|language=Japanese|accessdate=June 21, 2012}}</ref>

After a nearly eleven month absence from the ring, Yaegashi restarted his career, but lost in the semi-final match of the annual Japanese title elimination tournament nicknamed "The Strongest in Korakuen" at the [[Korakuen Hall]] in [[Tokyo]] in July 2008. It was in June 2009 that Yaegashi won the vacant Japanese minimumweight title at the IMP Hall in [[Osaka]]. He defended the title three times before returning it.<ref name="moxmob" />

Yaegashi won the WBA minimumweight title in his second world title shot against [[Thai people|Thai]]'s [[Pornsawan Porpramook]] via a tenth round technical knockout at the Korakuen Hall on October 24, 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bangkokpost.com/news/sports/263005/pornsawan-loses-wba-title|title=Pornsawan loses WBA title|date=October 25, 2011|publisher=''[[Bangkok Post]]''|accessdate=October 25, 2011}}</ref> It was a very tough fight.<ref>{{Cite video|date=October 24, 2011|title=Pornsawan Porpramook vs. Yaeagshi|url=https://www.youtube.com/user/TVTOKYO/videos?query=%22%EF%BC%B7%EF%BC%A2%EF%BC%A1%E4%B8%96%E7%95%8C%E3%83%9F%E3%83%8B%E3%83%9E%E3%83%A0%E7%B4%9A%E3%82%BF%E3%82%A4%E3%83%88%E3%83%AB%E3%83%9E%E3%83%83%E3%83%81%E3%80%80%E3%83%9D%E3%83%B3%E3%82%B5%E3%83%AF%E3%83%B3%C3%97%E5%85%AB%E9%87%8D%E6%A8%AB%22|medium=Links to [[YouTube]] video|language=Japanese|publisher=[[TV Tokyo]]|accessdate=June 20, 2012}}</ref> Before the final round began, Yaegashi's manager Ohashi said to him "Come back for your son". The fight earned accolades from international media, winning Fight of the Year honors from [[ESPN|ESPN.com]]<ref name="espnfoty">{{Cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/boxing/story/_/id/7404167/akira-yaegashi-pornsawan-porpramook|title=Fight of year: Yaegashi-Porpramook|author=Dan Rafael|date=December 30, 2011|publisher=[[ESPN]]|accessdate=June 20, 2012}}</ref> and BoxingScene.com,<ref name="boxingscenefoty">{{Cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/?m=show&opt=printable&id=48078|title=BoxingScene's 2011 Year-End Awards: Fight of The Year|author=Cliff Rold|date=January 3, 2012|publisher=BoxingScene.com|accessdate=June 20, 2012}}</ref> as well as the WBA's award for Most Dramatic Fight of 2011.<ref name="bangkokpost20120204">{{Cite web|url=http://www.bangkokpost.com/print/278246/|title=Ex-champion Khaosai named WBA legend|author=Kittipong Thongsombat|date=February 4, 2012|publisher=''Bangkok Post''|accessdate=June 21, 2012}}</ref>

On June 20, 2012, in a match that marked the first time two Japanese fighters had met to unify world titles, he lost to the WBC champion [[Kazuto Ioka]] via a unanimous decision at the [[Osaka Prefectural Gymnasium|Bodymaker Colosseum]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ringtv.craveonline.com/blog/173457|title=Ioka bests valiant Yaegashi to unify strawweight titles|author=[[Corey Erdman]]|date=June 20, 2012|publisher=[[The Ring (magazine)|RingTV.com]]|accessdate=June 20, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.queensberry-rules.com/2012-articles/june/kazuto-ioka-decisions-one-eyed-akira-yaegashi-in-minimumweight-title-tilt.html|title=Kazuto Ioka Decisions One-Eyed Akira Yaegashi In Minimumweight Title Tilt|author=Mark Ortega|date=June 20, 2012|publisher=Queensberry-Rules.com|accessdate=June 20, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/?m=show&opt=printable&id=54174|title=Kazuto Ioka Outlasts Akira Yaegashi In A War|author=Jake Donovan|date=June 20, 2012|publisher=BoxingScene.com|accessdate=June 20, 2012}}</ref> When asked whether the result would have been different unless he got swollen eyes, Yaegashi said "We should not think about it. There is no if's in boxing".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sankei.jp.msn.com/sports/news/120620/mrt12062023090002-n1.htm|title=敗者、八重樫に涙なし　「またイチから…」|author=藤原 翔|date=June 20, 2012|publisher=[[Sankei Shimbun|MSN Sankei News]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=June 20, 2012}}</ref> The day after the fight, Ioka decided to move up a weight division. So, Yaegashi's team hope the rematch with Ioka in a higher division as their second unification bout. First, Yaegashi aims to win a world championship again.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sponichi.co.jp/battle/news/2012/06/22/kiji/K20120622003516060.html|title=井岡と八重樫　ライトフライ級で再戦誓う|date=June 22, 2012|publisher=''[[Sports Nippon]]''|language=Japanese|accessdate=June 21, 2012 (UTC)}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.daily.co.jp/ring/2012/06/22/0005154353.shtml|title=八重樫「悔しい」井岡との再戦に意欲|date=June 22, 2012|publisher=''Daily Sports''|language=Japanese|accessdate=June 21, 2012 (UTC)}} (includes photo)</ref>

Yaegashi returned to the ring in a 110-pound bout at the Korakuen Hall on January 5, 2013 to knock out Saenmuangloei Kokietgym in the ninth round.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/?m=show&opt=printable&id=61108|title=Akira Yaegashi A Knockout Winner In Ring Return|author=Jake Donovan|date=January 5, 2013|publisher=BoxingScene.com|accessdate=January 6, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fightnews.com/Boxing/inoue-finishes-thai-champ-ngaoprajan-in-one-159504|title=Inoue finishes Thai champ Ngaoprajan in one|author=Joe Koizumi|date=January 5, 2013|publisher=Fightnews.com|accessdate=January 6, 2013}}</ref>

